        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The requested correlator setup provides 3.3 resolution elements across each line - sufficient to resolve the line.  The justification for the window width is provided with the data rate justification, below.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We are requesting a modest increase in spatial resolution from that of Qi et al. (2013), in anticipation of resolving additional spatial structure if sufficient C3H+ emission is present.  In the worst-case scenario of an abundance ratio of 0.04, the observations can be readily spatially-smoothed to the 0.8" beam size of Qi et al. (2013), which will provide a 3 sigma detection in each beam.

Fig 1 of Qi et al. (2013) demonstrates the largest angular scale shown for c-C3H2, and we expect a similar structure for C3H+ based on the work of Guzman et al. (2015).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have measured fractional abundances of C3H+ relative to c-C3H2 of 0.04 - 0.15 across a number of PDR sources.  Here, we assume likely fractional abundance of 0.10.

Using this abundance ratio, accounting for molecule-specific parameters (partition function, line intensities, energy levels, etc.), and using the integrated intensity of the c-C3H2 6-5 line of 185 mJy km/s in the 0.9" x 0.7" from Qi et al. (2013), we expect an integrated intensity of the C3H+ 10-9 transition at 224868 MHz to be 22.2 mJy km/s in the 0.9" x 0.7" beam.  Here, we have assumed that c-C3H2 and C3H+ will have similar excitation temperatures to those displayed (rather consistently) in PDR sources, where c-C3H2 is ~60 K, and C3H+ is quite sub-thermal at ~20 K.  Variations of up to 30% in either of these values does not change our detection threshold by more than a factor of ~2 in either direction.

Taking the linewidth to be 4.28 km/s (Guilloteau et al. 2013, A&amp;A, 549, A92), that gives a peak flux of 5.2 mJy in the 0.9" x 0.7" beam.

In the worst-case scenario, where the C3H+/c-C3H2 ratio falls on the lowest end of our measured spectrum (0.04), the peak flux would be 2.1 mJy per 0.9" x 0.7" beam.

We therefore request an RMS noise level of 700 uJy over a 1.3 km/s spectral resolution element.  Such a level provides a firm detection (~8 sigma) for our expected intensity, and, even in the worst-case scenario, provides a 3 sigma detection.  Thus, even in the worst-case scenario, we still expect an impactful scientific return.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Even at only 6 hours of ALMA time, this will be one of the most sensitive spectral line observations of a disk taken to date.

Given the known, rich molecular complexity in HD 163296, and the intense interest in "trace" molecular species in these objects (see, e.g. Oberg et al. 2015, Nature, 520, 198 and Walsh et al. 2014, A&amp;A, 563, A33), it would be a waste of valuable observing time to not target as many additional molecular species as possible commensally to the C3H+ observations.

As described in the Science Justification, we request commensal broadband line survey observations, which we will make publicly-available in a fully-reduced form.

We feel this more than justifies a data rate of only 2x the standard value.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
