    <prp:abstract>UV irradiation of the gas and dust in circumstellar disks plays a key role in driving both the chemistry and physics of the evolving disk. Accurate measurements not only of the intensity of this radiation, but of its physical extent, is essential for the refinement of models which will be informing the direction of research into these disks in the coming years with ALMA.

Currently, c-C3H2 is used as a tracer of the impact of UV on a disk, due to the dependence of its formation and destruction on this UV.  However, we have recently found that the l-C3H+ cation is a far more exquisitely sensitive tracer of UV enhancement - likely the best molecular tracer known to date.  Based on our work, we expect l-C3H+ emission to be detectable and spatially-resolvable in the HD 163296 circumstellar disk where Qi et al. (2013) have previously mapped c-C3H2.  We propose ALMA observations of this disk targeting l-C3H+ to both refine our understanding of the spatial extent of UV enhancement in this disk, and to determine the feasibility of using l-C3H+ as a sensitive tracer of such enhancement toward other targets.</prp:abstract>
